63
00:05:43,718 --> 00:05:46,804
THE ECHOES OF SURVIVORS:
INSIDE KOREA'S TRAGEDIES

64
00:05:54,729 --> 00:05:57,023
How many years were you locked up for?

65
00:06:01,361 --> 00:06:04,530
They took me away when I was 11

66
00:06:05,031 --> 00:06:07,533
and didn't let me go until I was 18 or 19.

67
00:06:10,411 --> 00:06:12,080
So it was about eight years.

68
00:06:16,501 --> 00:06:20,713
I was there for a little more
than four years and six months.

69
00:06:24,384 --> 00:06:27,095
I think I was there for about 11 years.

70
00:06:32,058 --> 00:06:33,768
I was taken in when I was 11.

71
00:06:34,685 --> 00:06:38,481
And I got out when I was 18.
My father came for me.

72
00:06:41,109 --> 00:06:43,152
Sir, did you receive any education?

73
00:06:43,653 --> 00:06:45,237
No, I didn't receive any in there.

74
00:06:45,238 --> 00:06:48,324
What is your highest level
of formal education, sir?

75
00:06:48,783 --> 00:06:49,784
None.

76
00:06:50,326 --> 00:06:53,161
We all thought it was okay
not to get an education.

77
00:06:53,162 --> 00:06:54,538
We didn't know any law.

78
00:06:54,539 --> 00:06:58,292
We didn't know about compulsory education,
and we were locked up too.

79
00:06:58,918 --> 00:07:01,504
I didn't go to school
while I was in there.

80
00:07:02,463 --> 00:07:05,508
I just barely learned to read.

81
00:07:06,300 --> 00:07:10,846
I struggle with calculations
when the numbers get too big.

82
00:07:10,847 --> 00:07:14,225
I can't even hope to do
multiplication or division.

83
00:07:15,101 --> 00:07:17,185
The director believed,

84
00:07:17,186 --> 00:07:21,314
"If we give these little punks a break,
they'll try to run."

85
00:07:21,315 --> 00:07:24,861
"Don't let them just sit around.
Put them to work."

86
00:07:25,611 --> 00:07:29,240
A seven-year-old was put to work
doing manual labor.

87
00:07:30,741 --> 00:07:33,118
We hardly ate,

88
00:07:33,119 --> 00:07:35,496
yet they worked us to the bone.

89
00:07:36,456 --> 00:07:38,623
We were on the verge of fainting,

90
00:07:38,624 --> 00:07:43,004
working all day on empty stomachs
in the middle of summer.

91
00:07:46,174 --> 00:07:49,135
We were always hungry.
They hardly fed us anything.

92
00:07:50,052 --> 00:07:52,137
They'd give us meat soup,

93
00:07:52,138 --> 00:07:54,931
but it was just oil floating around.

94
00:07:54,932 --> 00:07:57,309
That stuff was just inedible.

95
00:07:57,310 --> 00:08:00,396
There was hardly anything
you could actually call food.

96
00:08:00,980 --> 00:08:03,565
They gave us barley rice,

97
00:08:03,566 --> 00:08:06,903
but it was barely three spoonfuls' worth.

98
00:08:08,029 --> 00:08:11,615
And the soup tasted like nothing more

99
00:08:11,616 --> 00:08:13,700
than water used to rinse <i>doenjang.</i>

100
00:08:13,701 --> 00:08:15,035
INMATES WAITING FOR SOY SOUP

101
00:08:15,036 --> 00:08:18,998
Most of the side dishes
smelled like they were rotten.

102
00:08:19,499 --> 00:08:22,375
Kimchi tasted like it had already spoiled.

103
00:08:22,376 --> 00:08:23,878
Whenever they went to a farm,

104
00:08:24,378 --> 00:08:27,673
it was always right after the cabbages
had been harvested.

105
00:08:28,674 --> 00:08:32,386
Around then, you'd find leaves
and peels tossed out in the fields.

106
00:08:32,887 --> 00:08:36,682
The farm owner was actually thankful
when someone cleaned it up.

107
00:08:38,017 --> 00:08:41,937
They would collect those leaves,
and the farm owner asked,

108
00:08:41,938 --> 00:08:45,899
"What on earth
do you need all of these for?"

109
00:08:45,900 --> 00:08:49,862
So they told him,
"We have about 30 pigs on our farm."

110
00:08:50,696 --> 00:08:52,990
"We're going to boil these up
for their food."

111
00:08:55,701 --> 00:08:58,245
It's great when all the fish
get auctioned off,

112
00:08:58,246 --> 00:09:02,375
but if they don't and sit for a few days,
the fish starts to spoil.

113
00:09:06,754 --> 00:09:07,672
We'd get a call.

114
00:09:08,172 --> 00:09:11,842
Then we'd bring the blue truck
to go pick up the mackerel.

115
00:09:13,177 --> 00:09:15,888
You can smell it
as soon as you start loading them.

116
00:09:17,723 --> 00:09:19,267
So when I first got there,

117
00:09:19,767 --> 00:09:23,104
they boiled and served spoiled fish,
so I couldn't eat it.

118
00:09:23,980 --> 00:09:27,149
I couldn't eat it.
I just couldn't. It was disgusting.

119
00:09:29,235 --> 00:09:32,572
<i>The director and his family eat here too.</i>

120
00:09:34,824 --> 00:09:37,367
<i>They are frying the fish they bought.</i>

121
00:09:37,368 --> 00:09:39,828
<i>They buy flour, bake bread,</i>

122
00:09:39,829 --> 00:09:42,707
<i>and serve it as snacks
once or twice a day.</i>

123
00:09:43,332 --> 00:09:48,087
<i>"Is 20,000 won a month really enough
to cover the meal I'm eating right now?"</i>

124
00:09:49,046 --> 00:09:50,380
Absolutely not.

125
00:09:50,381 --> 00:09:52,299
PASSENGERS AT THE FINAL STOP

126
